<!-- ================= EVACUATION SIMULATION INSIGHTS ================= -->
<section class="simulation-section container">

  <h2>Evacuation Simulation Insights</h2>
  <p class="sim-intro">
    Real-world evacuation simulations help us understand human movement, crowd density,
    congestion points, and alternate escape routes. These insights guide safer building designs
    and effective emergency planning.
  </p>

  <div class="sim-block">
    <img src="/assets/media/main_architecture.jpg" class="sim-img">
    <div class="sim-text">
      <h3>1. Floor Architecture</h3>
      <p>
        Development consist of three different facilities with central courtyard.
        It helps to detect the best possible routes during the time of disaster.
        It helps to find the alternative routes when emergency route is block.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sim-block">
    <img src="/assets/media/floor_architecture.jpg" class="sim-img">
    <div class="sim-text">
      <h3>2. Multi-Floor Evacuation Modeling</h3>
      <p>
        This multi-floor simulation visualizes building-wide evacuation, displaying movement from each floor to the assembly point.
        It highlights how exits must handle synchronized crowd flow from multiple levels during emergencies.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sim-block">
    <img src="/assets/media/ss1.jpg" class="sim-img">
    <div class="sim-text">
      <h3>3. Crowd Movement Visualization</h3>
      <p>
        This simulation demonstrates how people naturally move toward exits during an emergency.
        Blue areas show lower density, while red spots indicate crowd buildup.  
        Understanding these patterns helps optimize corridor width and exit placements.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sim-block">
    <img src="/assets/media/ss2.jpg" class="sim-img">
    <div class="sim-text">
      <h3>4. Heatmap-Based Density Detection</h3>
      <p>
        The density heatmap highlights high-traffic regions inside the building.  
        This data is crucial for predicting stampede risks and ensuring adequate evacuation flow.
        The color bar on the right shows crowd pressure per square meter.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="sim-block">
    <img src="/assets/media/ss3.jpg" class="sim-img">
    <div class="sim-text">
      <h3>5. Staircase Evacuation Flow</h3>
      <p>
        Staircases are the most critical evacuation paths.  
        This stair-flow simulation shows how quickly congestion forms on narrow stairs.
        Color gradients help analyze crowd density and walking speed differences across floors.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

</section>



<!-- ================= OFFICE FLOOR DEMO ================= -->
<section class="demo container" id="demo-section">
  <h2>Office Floor Evacuation Demo</h2>
  <p>This example shows how the system reveals evacuation routes only when needed and adapts during a blocked exit scenario.</p>

  <button class="toggle-btn" id="showRoutesBtn">Show Evacuation Routes</button>

  <button class="toggle-btn blocked-btn" id="toggleScenarioBtn" style="display:none;">
    Show Blocked Exit Scenario
  </button>

  <div class="demo-wrapper">

    <!-- FLOOR PLAN -->
    <div class="floor">
      <div class="room room-office1">Office 1</div>
      <div class="room room-office2">Office 2</div>
      <div class="room room-office3">Office 3</div>

      <div class="corridor">Corridor</div>

      <div class="room room-reception">Reception</div>
      <div class="room room-meeting">Meeting Room</div>
      <div class="room room-pantry">Pantry</div>

      <div class="exit-main">Main Exit (Stairs)</div>
      <div class="exit-emergency">Emergency Exit</div>

      <div class="hazard-area hidden" id="hazardArea"></div>
      <div class="blocked-icon hidden" id="blockedIcon">✖</div>

      <div class="route primary pr1 hidden"></div>
      <div class="route primary pr2 hidden"></div>
      <div class="route primary pr3 hidden"></div>

      <div class="route alt ar1 hidden"></div>
      <div class="route alt ar2 hidden"></div>
      <div class="route alt ar3 hidden"></div>

      <div class="person-dot hidden" id="personDot"></div>

    </div>

      <div class="demo-text">
      <h3>How to use this demo</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>By default, only the architecture is visible.</li>
        <li>Click <b>“Show Evacuation Routes”</b> to reveal the glowing green primary route.</li>
        <li>Then click <b>“Show Blocked Exit Scenario”</b> to see the red hazard and blue alternate safe route.</li>
        <li>The moving dot represents a person navigating to safety.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>This flow exactly represents how real buildings behave during disasters.</p>
    </div>

  </div>
</section>



